ce:section.ce:para:
The most practical thermal–hydraulic performance indicators for heat exchangers of this type are the effective thermal conductance (h) and pressure drop (ΔP) as a function of total volumetric flow rate. Figs. 11 and 12

                         show the experimental results for the fabricated FINJET unit along with the simulated results of [27]. Fig. 11 shows reasonable agreement between the simulated and measured thermal conductance, though inevitable discrepancies exist which tend to increase with increasing flow rate due to the power law variation of Nu with Re. However, at the nominal target flow rate of 0.5 L/min, the difference is ~15% which can be considered acceptable considering the idealizations imposed in the CFD simulation, in particular that of simulating an interior slice of the overall system, thus not considering any 3D effects within the plenum and interior channel. Also plotted in Fig. 11 is the average surface temperature rise above the inlet water temperature for both the simulated and measured cases. Agreement here can be considered very good, which establishes confidence in both the simulations and characterization facility and procedure. With regard to the pressure drop, Fig. 12 shows reasonable agreement between measurement and simulation, though the discrepancy is worse than that of the heat transfer results. This discrepancy is a result of the assembly process associated with the soldering of the plenum to jet-channel section. A postmortem analysis has revealed the presence of unwanted material residue (Fig. 13
                        ), verified by chemical analysis as byproducts of the soldering process, within the plenum. This material interferes with the flow at the inlet of the jet nozzles and, because this is a region of significant pressure drop in the system, ostensibly small imperfections will have a disproportionate influence on the overall pressure drop. Due to the length of the nozzles, which are several hydraulic-diameters in length, the influence on the heat transfer would not be expected to be as large, which indeed is the case here.
